    <learningContentbody>
        <lcInstruction>
            <p>The DITA OT can produce HTML output using the xhtml and html5 plugins. This lesson
                uses the xhtml plugin to demonstrate the process of publishing HTML output. </p>
            <p>To generate XHTML output, use the same content as the PDF exercise. Seeing the same
                content in two different output types gives you a firsthand look at the way DITA
                separates content from formatting.</p>
            <p><xref href="https://youtu.be/2qHoEHd7org" format="html" scope="external">Video:
                    Generating HTML Output</xref></p>
        </lcInstruction>
    </learningContentbody>
    <task id="task_kth_1dh_2z">
        <title>Generating HTML output</title>
        <taskbody>
            <steps id="steps_php_1ch_2z">
                <step>
                    <cmd>Type the following commands into the command line:</cmd>
                    <info>
                        <p><b>On Windows:</b></p>
                        <pre>bin\dita -i [filepath]/sources/ducks/m_ducks.ditamap -f xhtml -o out/ducks_output -v</pre>
                        <p><b>On Mac:</b></p>
                        <pre>./bin/dita -i [filepath]/sources/ducks/m_ducks.ditamap -f xhtml -o out/ducks_output -v</pre>
                    </info>
                </step>
                <step>
                    <cmd>Press ENTER to run the DITA OT.</cmd>
                </step>
                <step>
                    <cmd>Navigate to your <b>ducks_output</b> folder.</cmd>
                    <info>In addition to the PDF files you generated earlier, you should now see
                        multiple XHTML files and an <b>images</b> folder.</info>
                </step>
                <step>
                    <cmd>Open the file <b>index.html</b> in a browser.</cmd>
                    <info>
                        <p>This index file serves as an electronic table of contents, showing the
                            hierarchy of your map with links to each topic file. The DITA OTâ€™s
                            default xhtml plugin does not provide navigation, but the index file can
                            help you find the topics you need.</p>
                    </info>
                </step>
                <step>
                    <cmd>Open the file <b>c_duckling_growth.html</b> in a browser to see how the
                        xhtml plugin displays images and tables.</cmd>
                    <info><p>The default XHTML output looks like this:</p><image
                            href="images/xhtml_default_images.png" width="500" id="image_efp_dwl_3z"
                            /><note>Fonts and spacing may vary depending on which browser and
                            version you are using.</note></info>
                </step>
            </steps>
        </taskbody>
    </task>
